          "body": "The chapter's opening formula — 'these are the last words of David' followed immediately by the double *neum* ('oracle' or 'utterance') — is the key to everything that follows. The *neum* formula is the prophets' standard introduction for a divine communication; it appears hundreds of times in the Old Testament but only here attributed to a king rather than a named prophet. David does not say 'I hereby compose my final reflections'; he says 'The Spirit of the LORD spoke by me, and His word was on my tongue' (v. 2). This is one of the Old Testament's most direct claims to verbal inspiration: the agent of the oracle is the Spirit, the tongue is David's, but the word belongs to God. The apostle Peter cites this exact understanding when explaining the Psalms in Acts 2:30-31, and the author of Hebrews treats Davidic psalms as the speech of the Spirit (Hebrews 3:7). 2 Samuel 23 is not David's personal farewell; it is the Spirit's verdict through David on what covenant kingship is, what it secures, and what it will ultimately do to those who oppose it. To read it as mere biography is to miss its authority entirely."
