        "excerpt": "The Spirit of the LORD spoke by me, and His word was on my tongue.",
        "body": "The double *neum* formula of verse 1 — 'The oracle of David son of Jesse, the oracle of the man raised on high' — is the chapter's first interpretive surprise. *Neum* is the exclusive vocabulary of prophetic utterance in the Hebrew Bible, used by Isaiah, Jeremiah, Ezekiel, Amos, and the other writing prophets to signal that what follows comes from the mouth of God, not the imagination of the speaker. It appears only here on the lips of a king. The narrator is establishing from the first line that what follows is not political testament or personal wisdom — it is prophecy.\n\nVerse 2 then states the theology of that prophecy with unusual clarity: 'The Spirit of the LORD spoke by (*be*) me, and His word was on my tongue.' The preposition *be* in Hebrew can mean 'through' or 'by means of' — David is the instrument, the Spirit is the Speaker. This is precisely the theology of verbal inspiration that Peter articulates in 2 Peter 1:20-21: 'no prophecy of Scripture is a matter of one's own interpretation... but men moved by the Holy Spirit spoke from God.' Paul cites Davidic psalms as the Spirit's words (Romans 15:3; Hebrews 3:7). The chapter's opening two verses are therefore not merely David's personal piety; they are a claim about the nature of Scripture itself.\n\nThe fourfold self-identification in verse 1 — 'David son of Jesse,' 'the man raised on high,' 'the anointed of the God of Jacob,' 'the sweet psalmist of Israel' — traces a trajectory from ordinary origin to extraordinary vocation. Son of Jesse is shepherd-class, from a minor clan of Bethlehem. 'Raised on high' (*qamay*) recalls the language of 2 Samuel 7:8: 'I took you from the pasture, from following the sheep, to be ruler over My people Israel.' 'Anointed' (*mashiach*) is the covenant term that reaches beyond David to the eschatological king his line will produce. 'Sweet psalmist of Israel' (*naim zamirot yisrael*) honors the poet-worshipper who gave the covenant community its language of prayer. All four titles are necessary context for what follows: the oracle comes from a man who knows exactly who he is in God's economy — instrument, not originator.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Neum* (oracle/utterance) appears over 370 times in the OT, almost exclusively in prophetic books — its use twice in v. 1 is exegetically significant. *Ruach YHWH* (Spirit of the LORD) is the same agent who rushed upon David at his anointing (1 Samuel 16:13). *Mashiach* (anointed) is the precise Hebrew behind the Greek *Christos* — the chapter's opening verse already places David in the typological stream that flows to Jesus of Nazareth."
