        "title": "The ideal ruler and the morning without clouds — a Messianic standard no Davidic king met",
        "range": "23:3-4",
        "excerpt": "He who rules over men righteously, who rules in the fear of God, is as the light of the morning when the sun rises, a morning without clouds.",
        "body": "The oracle pivots in verse 3 to the Rock of Israel's speech about the ideal ruler. Two characteristics define him: ruling *people* righteously (*tsaddiq*, in justice) and ruling *in the fear of God* (*yirat elohim*). The pairing is crucial. The fear of God is not merely one virtue among many but the *mode* of righteous rule — without the vertical accountability of the fear of God, justice becomes either arbitrary or self-serving. The phrase anticipates what Proverbs 8:15-16 will make programmatic: kings reign righteously because wisdom — grounded in the fear of the LORD — is the foundation of all legitimate governance.\n\nThe morning metaphor (v. 4) is the oracle's most sustained image and deserves close reading. 'The light of the morning when the sun rises, a morning without clouds, when the tender grass springs out of the earth, through sunshine after rain' — the image is the Palestinian landscape's most abundant moment: the spring morning after a winter rain, when the low angle of the sunrise breaks through clouds that have given way, and the earth that has been watered is already visibly greening. The righteous ruler does not merely maintain order; his governance causes *life to emerge*. The metaphor moves from light (clarity, revelation) through warmth (the sun's energy) to growth (tender grass, *deshe*, the earliest spring shoot). This is not a description of what the ruler does; it is a description of what happens *to the people* under his rule.\n\nNo Israelite king fully embodied this standard. The books of Kings will catalog the near-universal failure of David's successors. Even David himself — whose moral failures bulk large in 2 Samuel 11-20 — could not sustain the morning without clouds. The standard is therefore not merely aspirational; it is messianic by necessity. The one ruler who will govern both righteously and in the fear of God, and under whose reign the tender grass of human flourishing will spring from the earth, is the Son of David whose throne will be established forever (2 Samuel 7:13; cf. Isaiah 11:1-5; Jeremiah 23:5-6). Reformed commentators from Calvin (Commentary on the Psalms) to Charles Spurgeon (The Treasury of David) consistently read this oracle as pointing to Christ precisely because no one else has ever met the standard it describes.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tsaddiq* (righteous, just) is the root of *tsedaqah* (righteousness), the covenant term for right relationship with God expressed in right conduct toward others. *Yirat elohim* (fear of God) is the seedbed of Israelite wisdom ethics (Proverbs 1:7; 9:10). *Deshe* (tender grass, sprout) is used in Genesis 1:11 for the earth's first growth at creation — the morning metaphor subtly evokes new creation."
