        "number": 3,
        "title": "The everlasting covenant — David's dying confidence and the anchor of Messianic hope",
        "range": "23:5-7",
        "excerpt": "For He has made an everlasting covenant with me, ordered in all things, and secured; for all my salvation and all my desire, will He not indeed make it grow?",
        "body": "Verse 5 is the oracle's theological center and David's most personal confession. Read with full awareness of the preceding narrative, it is remarkable. The man who just described the righteous ruler as 'a morning without clouds' is the same man who arranged Uriah's murder (chap. 11), whose household erupted in rape, fratricide, and rebellion (chaps. 13-19), and who is about to commit the sin of the unauthorized census (chap. 24). He is not ignorant of his own moral record. His confidence, therefore, must rest on something other than his own consistency.\n\nWhat he rests on is the three-fold description of the covenant: *everlasting* (*olam*) — it exceeds any human lifespan or dynasty; *ordered in all things* (*arukah*) — its terms are comprehensive, not partial; *secured* (*shamar*) — it is guarded and kept, a verb used of God's watchful protection. These three attributes are unilaterally God's achievement: 'He has made' (*sum*) this covenant. David did not negotiate it; God established it in 2 Samuel 7 as a gift of grace. D. A. Carson (For the Love of God, vol. 1) notes that the Davidic covenant shares this asymmetry with the Abrahamic: the covenant's permanence depends entirely on the character of the One who made it, not the character of the one to whom it was made.\n\nDavid's rhetorical question — 'will He not indeed make it grow?' — projects covenant fulfillment forward past his death. Salvation (*yesah*) and desire (*chephets*) will grow from the covenant. The imagery echoes the morning metaphor: just as sunshine after rain produces tender grass, the everlasting covenant will produce salvation. The question expects a confident 'yes' — and the canonical answer is the Davidic Son whose kingdom has no end (Luke 1:32-33).\n\nThe oracle closes (vv. 6-7) with the counter-picture: the worthless (*beliyyaal*), who are thrust away like thorns. The metaphor is precise: thorns cannot be gathered by hand without injury; they require iron tools and finally fire. Those who oppose the covenant ruler face not merely defeat but eschatological destruction — 'completely burned with fire in their place' (v. 7). This is the apocalyptic note that closes many prophetic oracles: the blessing of the righteous and the burning of the wicked as the covenant's final two movements (cf. Psalm 1:3-6; Isaiah 10:17; Malachi 4:1-3).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Berit olam* (everlasting covenant) is the same phrase used for the Noahic covenant (Genesis 9:16), the Abrahamic covenant (Genesis 17:7), and the Priestly covenant (Numbers 25:13). The consistency of the phrase argues that all these covenants belong to a single divine covenantal program. *Beliyyaal* (worthless) in its fullest OT usage describes those who are fundamentally opposed to God's order — not merely moral failures but agents of chaos against the covenant community."
