        "number": 4,
        "title": "The Three who stood alone — valor as covenant instrument",
        "range": "23:8-17",
        "excerpt": "The LORD brought about a great victory that day; and the people returned after him only to strip the slain.",
        "body": "The transition from oracle to roster (v. 8) is abrupt by modern literary standards but natural in ancient historiography: the king has spoken his final word; now the record shows through whom his kingdom was built. The first tier of warriors — the Three — receives narrative vignettes rather than mere names, and each vignette is structured identically: a dangerous situation, the rest of Israel withdrawing or fleeing, one man standing and fighting past the point of human endurance, and then the theological refrain: 'the LORD brought about a great victory' (vv. 10, 12).\n\nEleazar's stand is the more graphic: his hand 'clung to the sword' after striking Philistines until his arm gave out. Peter Davids, in the context of New Testament labor language, notes that the Greek equivalent of this Hebrew phrase (*davaq*, to cleave, to stick) describes covenantal adhesion — Ruth cleaving to Naomi (Ruth 1:14), a man cleaving to his wife (Genesis 2:24). Eleazar's hand did not merely tire; it became one with the instrument of his fidelity. The army then returned 'only to strip the slain' — they came back to loot, not to fight; Eleazar had already won the battle God would use him to win.\n\nShammah's episode is deliberately contrasted in scale: not an army but a lentil field. The narrator does not apologize for the smallness of the stakes. Israel's peasant economy ran on legumes; lentil fields were not trivial agricultural assets. But more importantly, the theological refrain attached to Shammah's stand in a lentil field is identical to the refrain attached to Eleazar's stand in a major battle: 'the LORD brought about a great victory.' God is as present and decisive in the defense of a plot of lentils as in the defeat of a Philistine army. The warrior's call is to stand; the victory belongs to the LORD regardless of the theater.\n\nThe Bethlehem water episode (vv. 13-17) belongs to the same theology by inversion. Here the mighty men act not in battle but in love — not ordered by David but moved by his expressed longing. The risk they took to draw water from an enemy-held well was militarily irrational and personally extravagant. David's refusal to drink and his pouring out of the water as a libation 'to the LORD' is the chapter's most theologically loaded act: he takes what was offered to him at the cost of blood and returns it to the One to whom all blood belongs. The act simultaneously honors his men (he will not consume their sacrifice as casual refreshment) and worships God (he treats the most costly gift he has received as an offering, not a convenience). The word for 'poured out' (*nasakh*) is the standard Levitical term for a drink offering — David performs a priestly act.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Davaq* (clung, v. 10) is used in covenantal language throughout the OT for adhesion to God and to covenant partners. *Nasakh* (poured out, v. 16) is the technical term for the drink offering (*nesek*) prescribed in Numbers 15:1-12 — David treats the water as a sacred oblation, not merely a dramatic gesture."
